# RESTer — Revit Environment Standardization Tool
**Spec v0.8 · Pre-Development · Open Source · April 2026**

---

## 00 · Overview

An open source Revit environment standardization system for BIM managers and admins. Define curated toolset profiles, export them as profile files, and distribute them to users — resulting in a consistent, focused Revit environment across the company.

Free and open source. No commercial strings attached.

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Tool Name | RESTer |
| Target User | BIM managers, Revit admins, firm IT leads |
| Distribution | Open source — GitHub (pyRevit extension) |
| Platform | Windows — Revit 2024+ |
| Primary Language | Python — pyRevit extension |
| Profile Format | JSON — no external dependencies |
| Status | Pre-development — moving to UI design |
| Version | 0.8 — Planning spec |

### Three Surfaces

**Profile Manager — inside Revit**
Admin-facing pyRevit tool. Admins record tools directly from the Revit ribbon, assemble them into a tab layout, configure visibility and add-in rules, and export a profile file for distribution. Requires Revit to be running.

**Profile Selector — outside Revit**
User-facing standalone app. Users add profiles by pointing to a profile file shared by the admin — RESTer copies it to the install location. Users select which profile to load; the tool handles add-in activation and records the active profile selection. Run before opening Revit.

**Runtime Extension — Add-ins tab, always present**
The pyRevit extension runs silently at every Revit launch: reads the active profile file and builds the custom tab. Two buttons live on the Add-ins tab in a fixed RESTer panel — one shows the loaded profile name and links to the README, one opens the Profile Manager. The profile tab itself is purely tool content — no RESTer chrome.

> **Key Architecture Principle:** The runtime extension is identical across all profiles. All profile-specific configuration lives in the profile file. At runtime, each button invokes its command directly via `PostCommand(RevitCommandId)` — no shortcut file is read or written, no key combinations are assigned. The extension is a profile reader, a tab builder, and a command invoker.

---

## 01 · Problem Statement

Most Revit environments in practice are cluttered. Add-ins accumulate over time, ribbon tabs multiply, and users spend time navigating tools irrelevant to their current workflow. There is no native Revit mechanism for an admin to define and enforce a standardized, role-appropriate environment.

Existing workarounds — manual shortcut exports, group policy scripts, ad-hoc add-in management — are fragile, non-repeatable, and require significant technical knowledge to maintain.

### The Core Need

- **Standardization** — consistent environment across all users on a profile
- **Role focus** — only relevant tools visible for a given workflow
- **Low friction** — users should not need to configure anything themselves
- **Admin control** — one person defines and distributes the environment
- **Resilience** — should survive Revit updates and user tinkering gracefully

> **Design Philosophy:** The tool is for **trimming excess, not finding gold**. Users already know what they want. The goal is removing noise from their environment, not discovering new workflows.

