## 02 · Solution Concept

RESTer has a hard boundary: admin work happens inside Revit, user profile selection happens outside Revit. Inside Revit at runtime, the tool surfaces two fixed buttons on the Add-ins tab and nothing else.

### Entry Points

**Add-ins tab — RESTer panel (always present):** two buttons, always on the Add-ins tab regardless of what profile is loaded. First button shows the name of the currently loaded profile and links to the README, which explains how to use the Profile Selector. Second button opens the Profile Manager (admin tool).

**Profile Selector (outside Revit):** standalone app the user runs before opening Revit. Manages the user's library of added profiles and records the active profile selection when the user loads one.

The profile tab built from a loaded profile is purely tool content. No RESTer buttons or chrome appear on it.

**Profile Manager (inside Revit)**
Opened via the Profile Manager button on the Add-ins tab. Admin creates and edits profiles — records tools from the ribbon, assembles the tab layout, configures rules, and exports a profile file to share with users.

**Profile Selector (outside Revit)**
User adds a profile by navigating to a profile file shared by the admin. RESTer copies it to the install location. User selects which profile to activate — the tool manages `.addin.inactive` renames and records the active profile selection. User then opens Revit.

### Admin Flow

1. **Open the Tab Creator** — Admin clicks **Profile Manager** from the Revit ribbon. The Tab Creator opens in-process. The profile switcher in the header lists all existing profiles — admin selects one to edit, or chooses **+ New** to start a blank slate. There is no separate Profile Manager window — all profile management happens inside the Tab Creator.

2. **Record tools** — Admin clicks **Record**. The extension subscribes to `ComponentManager.ItemExecuted` via `adwindows.dll`. Admin clicks tools in the Revit ribbon — each click captures the `CommandId`, display name, and icon and adds it to the Available Tools list. Tools can only be recorded once. Done ends recording.

3. **Create panels and stacks** — Admin creates panels using the + control in the Panels section of the browser. Stacks are created using the + control in the Stacks section — each new stack must be assigned to an existing panel. Stacks belong to exactly one panel and cannot be shared or reused. Panels must exist before stacks can be assigned to them.

4. **Add tools to panels and stacks** — Admin selects a panel or stack in the browser to open the editor. **Add Tool** shows available unplaced tools — admin picks from the list. Each tool can only be placed once. If no panel or stack exists when Add Tool is clicked, a nudge prompts the admin to create one first.

5. **Build the tab in preview** — Admin drags panels from the browser into the Tab Preview to place them. Panels can be reordered by dragging within the preview. Selecting a panel or stack in the preview opens the editor — everything remains editable as the preview builds.

6. **Declare required add-ins, mark tabs to hide** — Admin types required add-in names into the chip field in the header — autocompleted from add-ins active in the running Revit session. Each chip represents one declared dependency. To hide a tool's source add-in tab from profile users, admin clicks the hide toggle (–/✕) on that tool's row in the browser sidebar. The same toggle applies to stacks and panels.

7. **Export and share** — Admin clicks **Export Config** — enabled only when both the profile name and tab name fields are filled. Profile file written as `{profile-name}_{date}.json` to the admin's chosen location. Shared with users via any method — users add it in the Profile Selector.

### User Flow — Profile Selector

1. **Add a profile (first time)** — User clicks **Add Profile** and navigates to the profile file shared by the admin. RESTer copies the file to its install location and adds it to the user's profile list. This only needs to happen once per profile.

2. **Select profile to load** — User picks from their list of added profiles and clicks Load. Revit must be closed — the Profile Selector enforces this by disabling the Load button when any Revit.exe process is detected, re-enabling it automatically once the process is gone.

3. **Record active profile selection** — The active profile selection is recorded. User opens Revit — the runtime extension reads the active profile file and builds the tab automatically.

> **Remove Profile:** User can remove any added profile from their list at any time. This deletes the copied profile file from the RESTer install location. It does not affect the original file shared by the admin. If the removed profile was the active one, RESTer clears the active profile state. On the next Revit launch, the runtime extension detects no active profile and prompts the user to open the Profile Selector and load one. This same prompt handles first run — no special onboarding flow required.

> **Every Subsequent Launch:** On every Revit load, the runtime extension reads the active profile file and rebuilds the tab. No user action required unless switching profiles.

