## 05 · Add-in Detection

The system detects installed add-ins in two contexts: in the Tab Creator header to autocomplete the required add-ins chip field, and in the Profile Selector to surface visual flags against declared dependencies.

### Detection Method

- Scan both **per-user** and **per-machine** `.addin` manifest file locations on disk
- Detect add-in name, version (where populated), and active/inactive status
- Does **not** require Revit to be running — file scan only
- Profile Selector compares declared required add-ins from the profile JSON against detected add-ins and shows a visual flag per missing entry. No detection occurs inside Revit at runtime.

### Recording Requires Revit Open

Tool capture via recording requires Revit to be open — the `ComponentManager.ItemExecuted` event from `adwindows.dll` is only available in an active Revit session. Add-in detection for dependency management works with Revit closed or open.

**Revit Closed:** Can detect installed add-ins via .addin files for dependency management. Cannot capture tools — recording requires an active Revit session.

**Revit Open:** Full tool capture via recording — any ribbon button can be registered. Add-in detection also available. Required for profile creation.

> **Scope Decision:** This tool only supports add-ins that register their commands correctly as ribbon items — the standard for any modern, well-built add-in. If a command doesn't produce a valid, `PostCommand`-compatible `CommandId` when clicked during recording, it will be rejected at capture time with a clear message. Supporting non-registering add-ins is explicitly out of scope — that is an add-in quality problem, not ours to solve.

