## 08 · Custom Tab Builder

The runtime extension builds a custom Revit ribbon tab from the profile definition using the pyRevit ribbon API. The tab contains panels grouping curated tool buttons. Each button invokes its command directly via `PostCommand(RevitCommandId)` when clicked.

### Tab Structure

- **Tab** — one tab per profile, named by the admin. The tab name is the ribbon tab label users will see in Revit.
- **Panels** — maximum 4 panels per tab, each with a custom name and background color. Color is set via hex code entry — admin types a hex value and can save it as a swatch for reuse. No color picker widget. Confirmed supported via pyRevit ribbon API.
- **Tools** — each tool occupies one slot in a panel as a full-size button. Each tool can only appear once across the entire profile. Tools support an optional accent color set via hex code, applied to the button icon or label treatment in the ribbon.
- **Stacks** — a stack is a compact grouping of up to 3 tools displayed as a single stacked button unit in the ribbon. Stacks are created inside a panel, belong to that panel only, and cannot be shared or reused. A stack occupies one slot in its parent panel.
- **Capacity** — 4 panels per tab. The number of tools and stacks per panel is not hard-capped in the spec — the practical limit is what displays cleanly in a Revit ribbon panel. This should be validated during the POC and a recommended maximum documented. A stack counts as one item in its parent panel and holds up to 3 tools.
- **Add-in tab hide rules** — applied at load time per the profile file. Set via the hide toggle on sidebar items in the Tab Creator. Optional; default is all tabs visible.

> **Design Constraint:** One tab per profile. The profile tab is purely tool content — no RESTer chrome. RESTer's own buttons live on the Add-ins tab and are never mixed into the profile tab layout.

### Tab Preview

The lower region of the Tab Creator shows a live preview of the tab as it will appear in Revit. Panels are dragged from the browser into the preview to place them. Panels can be reordered by dragging left and right within the preview. Selecting any panel or stack in the preview opens the editor for that object — the admin can continue editing without leaving the preview context.

### Button Behaviour

1. **User clicks button** — Button click handler fires in the extension.
2. **PostCommand invocation** — Extension calls `UIApplication.PostCommand(RevitCommandId)` for this button's stored CommandId. Revit queues the command for execution.
3. **Handle failure gracefully** — If the command cannot execute in the current context (wrong view type, dialog open, etc.), surface a clear, non-alarming message rather than failing silently.

> **⚠ API Fragility:** The pyRevit ribbon API is version-sensitive. Changes between Revit releases may break tab or panel construction. Initial support scoped to Revit 2024+. Community to submit version-specific fixes as needed.

