## 10 · UI Reference

A catalogue of every UI element in the tool, organized by context. Intended for design and implementation review. Elements are described by function — visual treatment is left to the design phase.

### Add-ins Tab — RESTer Panel

Always present in Revit, regardless of what profile is loaded. Two buttons, side by side in a fixed RESTer panel.

**Profile Indicator** — Shows the name of the currently loaded profile. Links to the README, which explains the Profile Selector. Primary touchpoint for end users — they can see what profile they're on and learn how to change it.

**Profile Manager** — Opens the Profile Manager window. Admin tool. Accessible to any user in the UI — if a non-admin opens it, the empty state makes clear it is for profile authors.

### Profile Manager Window (inside Revit)

There is no separate Profile Manager window. The Tab Creator is the single surface for all profile management. It opens directly when the admin clicks the Profile Manager button on the Add-ins tab.

### Tab Creator Window

Opens when the admin clicks the Profile Manager button on the Add-ins tab. Three regions: a browser sidebar on the left, a panel/stack editor in the centre, and a tab preview at the bottom. All three stay live simultaneously — edits made in any region are immediately reflected in the others.

#### Header

- **Profile switcher** — dropdown listing all locally saved profiles by name. Selecting a profile loads it for editing. A **+ New** entry at the bottom of the dropdown creates a blank profile. A pencil (rename) button beside the switcher allows renaming the current profile inline. This is the complete profile management surface — create, switch, and rename all live here.
- **Delete profile** — accessible via the profile switcher context. Confirmation prompt before deletion. If the last profile is deleted, the creator returns to a blank state.
- **Required add-ins chip field** — text input with autocomplete sourced from add-ins active in the running Revit session. Each confirmed entry becomes a chip. Chips can be removed individually. All declared add-ins are treated as required — no per-chip toggle. The full chip list is written to the profile JSON on export and read by the Profile Selector to surface missing dependency flags.
- **Tab name field** — text input. Sets the ribbon tab label users will see in Revit. Required before export.
- **Revit version indicator** — read-only status display. Shows the Revit version detected from the active session. Written to the profile JSON as `min_version` on export. Not editable.
- **Export Config button** — disabled and visually greyed until both the profile name and tab name fields are non-empty. Clicking it validates the profile and writes `{profile-name}_{date}.json` to the admin's chosen location.

#### Browser Sidebar

Three sections in a fixed left column: Available Tools, Stacks, Panels. This is the source of truth for the entire profile — every object in the profile exists here first. Every row in all three sections has a hide toggle.

- **Available Tools** — list of all tools captured via recording. Each entry shows the resolved tool name and icon. A checkmark indicates the tool has been placed in a panel or stack. Unplaced tools show no checkmark. The **Record** button sits inline in the section header — enters recording mode when clicked.
- **Hide toggle (–/✕)** — present on every row across all three sidebar sections. Inactive state (–) is neutral. Active state (✕) uses amber styling to indicate the item is hidden. When active, the source add-in's native Revit tab is suppressed for profile users at runtime. Toggling does not affect tool placement or panel/stack membership — it is purely a tab visibility setting.
- **Stacks** — list of all stacks created for this profile, with a + control to add a new stack. The + is disabled until at least one panel exists. Each stack entry shows its name, parent panel indicator, and tool count. A checkmark on a stack indicates its parent panel has been placed in the Tab Preview.
- **Panels** — list of all panels created for this profile, with a + control to add a new panel. Each panel entry shows its color dot and name. A checkmark indicates the panel has been dragged into the Tab Preview.

#### Empty State

When a new Tab Creator opens, all three browser sections are empty and the preview is empty. The only available actions are Record Tool and the + control on the Panels section. The Stacks + control is disabled until a panel exists. The editor centre region shows a prompt directing the admin to start by recording tools or creating a panel. Export Config is not visible.

- **No tools recorded yet** — Tools list shows an empty state with a prompt to use Record Tool.
- **No stacks created yet** — Stacks list shows an empty state with a note that a panel must exist first. The + control is disabled.
- **No panels created yet** — Panels list shows an empty state with a prompt to create a panel using +.
- **Nothing in preview** — Tab Preview is empty. Export Config button is visible but disabled.

#### Tool Capture

- **Record Tool button** — enters recording mode: subscribes to `ComponentManager.ItemExecuted` via `adwindows.dll` and shows the recording indicator.
- **Recording indicator** — inline status element. Shows "Recording — click any tool in Revit." Persists until Done or Cancel is clicked. Non-modal — admin can interact with Revit freely.
- **Done button** — ends recording, unsubscribes from the event, returns focus to the Tab Creator. Only visible during active recording.
- **Cancel button** — ends recording without committing any tools captured in the current session. Only visible during active recording.
- **Capture success feedback** — brief inline notification each time a tool is successfully added. Shows the resolved tool name. Auto-dismisses.
- **Capture failure feedback** — inline notification when a clicked tool cannot be validated for `PostCommand` invocation. Explains briefly why. Auto-dismisses. Does not interrupt recording mode.

#### Panel / Stack Editor

Opens in the centre region when a panel or stack is selected — either from the browser sidebar or from the Tab Preview. The editor is context-aware: its available actions and fields depend on whether a panel or stack is selected. When nothing is selected, the centre region shows a prompt to select a panel or stack from the browser, or to create one first.

- **Add Tool button** — always present in the editor header when a panel or stack is selected. Opens a picker showing only unplaced tools. If no panel or stack has been created yet and the admin somehow triggers Add Tool, the nudge reads: "Create a panel or stack first." If a panel or stack is selected, the chosen tool is added to it immediately.
- **Panel name field** — shown when a panel is selected. Sets the panel label shown in the Revit ribbon.
- **Panel color field** — shown when a panel is selected. Admin types a hex value into the inline hex field and applies it. A row of saved swatches is shown for quick reuse — swatches are populated by saving hex values, not preset. No color picker widget.
- **Stack name field** — stacks do not have a visible label in the Revit ribbon. A stack name is shown in the Tab Creator for internal admin reference only — it helps the admin keep stacks straight while building the profile. Not surfaced to users at any point.
- **Tool list** — shows all tools currently placed in the selected panel or stack, in order. Supports drag-to-reorder within the list.
- **Tool color field** — per-tool, optional. Hex code input. Admin enters a hex value to apply an accent color to the tool's button in the Revit ribbon. Confirmed supported via Revit API. Defaults to no color if left blank.
- **Remove tool action** — per-tool in the list. Removes the tool from the panel or stack and returns it to the Tools section. Its checkmark clears.
- **Remove panel / stack action** — removes the selected object entirely. All its tools return to the Tools section. If the panel was in the preview, it is also removed from the preview and its checkmark clears. Confirmation prompt if the panel or stack contains tools.

#### Tab Preview

Persistent region at the bottom of the Tab Creator. Shows the tab as it will appear in Revit. Empty until the admin drags a panel in. Updates live as the admin edits panels and stacks.

- **Panel drop target** — admin drags a panel from the Panels browser into the preview to place it. Placing a panel sets its checkmark in the browser. Maximum 4 panels in the preview — the drop target is disabled once the limit is reached.
- **Panel reordering** — panels in the preview are draggable left and right to set their display order in the Revit ribbon.
- **Panel / stack selection** — clicking any panel or stack in the preview opens the editor for that object. The browser highlights the corresponding entry.
- **Remove from preview** — each panel in the preview has a remove control (distinct from the delete action in the editor). Removing from preview returns the panel to unplaced state — its checkmark clears, its tools and stacks remain intact and can be placed again. The panel still exists in the browser.
- **Export Config button** — always visible in the tab preview bar. Disabled and greyed until both the profile name and tab name fields are non-empty. Clicking it validates the profile and writes the profile file as `{profile-name}_{date}.json` to the admin's chosen location. This is the completion action for the Tab Creator.

#### Close

- **Cancel / Close button** — exits the Tab Creator and returns to the Profile Manager. Confirmation prompt if unsaved changes exist.

### Profile Selector (outside Revit)

Standalone app. User-facing. Manages the user's local library of added profiles and handles all profile switching before Revit launches.

- **Revit version dropdown** — shown at the top of the app. Populated automatically from local Revit installs detected on the machine. User selects which Revit install they are configuring. This is the primary context-setter — it determines which `.addin` manifest paths are targeted and filters profile compatibility display. Version should be selected before interacting with profiles.
- **Profile list** — shows all profiles the user has added. Each entry shows the profile name, declared min. Revit version, and required add-in flags. Empty state prompts the user to add a profile. Profiles whose `min_version` is newer than the selected Revit install are shown greyed out with a version mismatch indicator — they remain selectable at the user's own risk.
- **Required add-in flags** — each profile card shows a flag for every add-in declared in the profile's `requiredAddins` field that is not detected on the user's machine. Detection is a passive scan of `.addin` manifest file locations — no Revit process required. Present add-ins are silent. Missing add-ins are flagged by name. No block on loading — informational only.
- **Add Profile button** — opens a file picker. User navigates to a `.json` profile file provided by the admin. RESTer validates the file on add: if `min_version` is absent or the file is otherwise unreadable, it is rejected immediately with a clear error — it is not added to the library. Valid files are copied to the install location and added to the list. Only needs to happen once per profile.
- **Load button** — per-profile. Records the active profile selection. **Hard block if Revit is running** — the Load button is disabled (not just warned) when any `Revit.exe` process is detected. The reason is shown inline. The button re-enables automatically once the process is gone. No confirmation gate is required — the hard block is sufficient. After a successful load, user opens Revit normally.
- **Remove button** — per-profile. Removes the profile from the list and deletes the copied file from the install location. Does not affect the original file shared by the admin. Confirmation prompt before deletion. If the removed profile was the active one, the active profile state is cleared — on the next Revit launch the runtime prompts the user to load a profile via the Profile Selector.
- **Active profile indicator** — shows which profile is currently loaded for the selected Revit version. Persists across sessions.

> **⚠ Version Mismatch — User Accepted Risk:** If a profile's `min_version` is newer than the selected Revit install, the profile card shows a persistent inline version mismatch flag. Loading it is not blocked. No further handling is provided by the Profile Selector — the user proceeds at their own risk. Any tool failures at runtime surface a generic failure toast.

> **⚠ Corrupt Profile:** A profile file missing `min_version` or otherwise unreadable is treated as corrupt. It is rejected at the point of adding it in the Profile Selector and is never added to the user's library. A clear error message names the file and states it could not be read.

### Runtime — Profile Tab

The custom Revit ribbon tab built from the active profile file. Purely tool content — no RESTer buttons appear on the profile tab itself.

- **Profile tab** — named as set by the admin. Built on every Revit launch from the active profile file.
- **Panel buttons (large)** — full-slot buttons. Show tool name and icon. Click invokes the tool via `PostCommand`.
- **Panel buttons (small stack)** — 3-stack layout within a single slot. Same behaviour as large buttons but compact. Tool name truncated; full name shown on hover.
- **Failure toast** — non-blocking notification if `PostCommand` cannot execute. States that the profile may be incompatible with the running Revit version or the required add-in version may not be installed. Generic — does not name a specific command or add-in. Auto-dismisses.

